#let images = (
  "12.1": (
    caption: [Phloem translocates materials from sources to sinks. The diagram illustrates the overall process of phloem transport, showing short-distance pre-phloem transport from source tissues, phloem loading into collection phloem, long-distance transport through path phloem, phloem unloading from release phloem, and short-distance post-phloem transport to sink tissues. This represents the complete pathway for translocation of photosynthates and other materials.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.2": (
    caption: [Source-to-sink patterns of phloem translocation. Different patterns of translocation are shown depending on the developmental stage and position of plant organs. Mature leaves act as sources, while roots, developing leaves, fruits, and storage organs function as sinks. Bidirectional transport in the phloem allows flexible resource allocation throughout the plant body.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.3": (
    caption: [Transverse section of a vascular bundle of buttercup (Ranunculus repens). The primary phloem is located toward the outside of the stem. Both the primary phloem and the primary xylem are surrounded by a bundle sheath of thick-walled sclerenchyma cells, which isolate the vascular tissue from the ground tissue. Fibers and xylem vessels are stained red, showing the spatial organization of transport tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.4": (
    caption: [Transverse section of a 4-year-old stem of a basswood (Tilia) tree. The numbers 1, 2, and 3 indicate growth rings in the secondary xylem. The old (outer) secondary phloem is pushed outward by expansion of the xylem. Only the most recent (innermost) layer of secondary phloem is functional, demonstrating that active phloem tissue is limited to the newest growth.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.5": (
    caption: [Schematic drawings of mature sieve elements (sieve tube elements) joined together to form a sieve tube. (A) External view, showing sieve plates and lateral sieve areas. (B) Longitudinal section, showing two sieve tube elements connected to form a continuous sieve tube. The pores in the sieve plates between elements are open channels for transport. The plasma membrane is continuous between adjacent elements. Each sieve tube element is associated with one or more companion cells, which maintain metabolic functions. Note that companion cells have many organelles, whereas mature sieve tube elements have relatively few.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.6": (
    caption: [Electron micrographs of sieve elements and companion cells and their pore-plasmodesma contacts. Companion cells have dense cytoplasm, whereas sieve elements appear brighter due to their electron-translucent lumen. (A) Sieve element from castor bean hypocotyl associated with a companion cell strand of four cells. (B) Sieve element-companion cell complex from a potato minor vein showing nucleus, chloroplast, and mitochondria in the companion cell. A pore-plasmodesma contact is visible. (C) Pore-plasmodesma contacts symplasmically connect a sieve element and its companion cell in a potato leaf, with the sieve element plasma membrane lined with smooth ER cisternae.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.7": (
    caption: [Sieve elements and sieve plate pores. In images A-C, the sieve plate pores are open and unobstructed by P-protein or callose, providing a low-resistance pathway for transport. (A) Electron micrograph of longitudinal section of two mature sieve elements showing the sieve plate in winter squash hypocotyl. (B) Inset shows sieve plate pores in face view. (C) Section through a sieve plate in developing castor bean cotyledon with large pores and plastids, with filamentous P-protein dispersed throughout the cytoplasm. (D) Scanning electron microscope image of a castor bean sieve plate treated with protease to reveal the structure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.8": (
    caption: [Electron micrograph showing a sieve area linking two sieve cells in the secondary phloem of a conifer (Picea abies). Smooth endoplasmic reticulum covers the sieve area on both sides and is found within the pores and the extended median cavity. Such obstructed pores would result in high resistance to mass flow between sieve cells, contrasting with the open pores in angiosperm sieve tube elements.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.9": (
    caption: [Electron micrograph showing the relationships among phloem cell types in the smallest vein of a potato source leaf. The image shows two sieve elements, three large companion cells, and two phloem parenchyma cells, all surrounded by the bundle sheath. Photosynthates from the mesophyll are loaded from the bundle sheath or phloem parenchyma into the sieve element-companion cell complexes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.10": (
    caption: [Schematic diagram of pathways of phloem loading showing both symplasmic and apoplastic routes. Photosynthate can move from mesophyll cells to sieve elements either through continuous cytoplasmic connections via plasmodesmata (symplasmic pathway) or by exiting to the cell wall space and being actively transported across membranes (apoplastic pathway). Different plant species use different loading strategies.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.11": (
    caption: [Autoradiograph showing that labeled sugar moves from mesophyll cells to the phloem in a sugar beet leaf. After photosynthesis in the presence of radioactive carbon dioxide, the distribution of labeled photosynthate demonstrates the pathway from source cells to the vascular tissue for long-distance transport.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.12": (
    caption: [ATP-dependent sucrose transport in the phloem loading pathway. The diagram illustrates the chemiosmotic mechanism of sucrose uptake, where proton-sucrose symporters use the proton gradient generated by H+-ATPases to actively accumulate sucrose against its concentration gradient. This mechanism is essential for apoplastic phloem loading.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.13": (
    caption: [Electron micrographs of specialized companion cells called intermediary cells found in plants that use symplasmic phloem loading. These companion cells have distinctive structural features including numerous plasmodesmata connecting to bundle sheath cells and modified cell wall ingrowths that increase surface area for transport processes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.14": (
    caption: [Oligomer-trapping model of phloem loading. In this symplasmic loading mechanism, sucrose enters companion cells through plasmodesmata and is converted to larger oligosaccharides (raffinose family oligosaccharides) that cannot easily diffuse back. This creates a thermodynamic trap that maintains the concentration gradient for continued sucrose influx.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-12.1": (
    caption: [Characteristics of two types of sieve elements in seed plants. This table compares sieve tube elements found in angiosperms with sieve cells found in gymnosperms, highlighting differences in structure, organization, and functional characteristics that affect transport efficiency.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-12.2": (
    caption: [Patterns in apoplastic and symplasmic loading. The table summarizes the key differences between the two major phloem loading strategies, including the anatomical features, transport mechanisms, predominant sugars transported, and the plant families that utilize each strategy.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.15": (
    caption: [Pressure-flow model of translocation in the phloem. This widely accepted model explains how mass flow of phloem sap is driven by osmotically generated pressure gradients. Water enters the phloem at source regions where sugars are loaded, creating high turgor pressure. Water exits at sink regions where sugars are unloaded, creating low turgor pressure. This pressure difference drives bulk flow through the sieve tubes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.16": (
    caption: [Sieve plate pores and sieve tubes in electron micrographs and three-dimensional reconstruction. (A) Showing sieve plate structure with pores that facilitate transport between connected sieve elements. (B) Longitudinal view of phloem network in dahlia after clearing and staining with aniline blue, which binds to callose and fluoresces yellow. Sieve plates appear as numerous small dots, revealing the delicate interconnected phloem network with vascular anastomoses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.17": (
    caption: [Structures of compounds not normally translocated in the phloem versus those that are readily translocated. The figure demonstrates structure-function relationships, showing how molecular properties such as size, charge, and lipophilicity affect a compound's ability to enter and move through the phloem transport system.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-12.3": (
    caption: [The composition of phloem sap, collected as an exudate from cuts in the phloem. The table provides quantitative data on the major components of phloem sap including sugars (primarily sucrose), amino acids, organic acids, inorganic ions, proteins, and other molecules, demonstrating the complexity of the transported fluid.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.18": (
    caption: [Sealing of sieve elements by P-protein and callose deposition in response to wounding. When phloem tissue is damaged, P-protein rapidly plugs sieve plate pores, and callose is deposited to seal the wound and prevent loss of phloem sap. This demonstrates the plant's wound response mechanism to maintain phloem integrity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.19": (
    caption: [Pathways for phloem unloading and post-phloem transport to sink tissues. The diagram illustrates both symplasmic (through plasmodesmata) and apoplastic (across membranes) unloading routes. The pathway used depends on the sink tissue type and developmental stage, with some sinks using predominantly one route while others may switch between routes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.20": (
    caption: [Live imaging of translocation in and unloading from root protophloem sieve tubes. (A) GFP targeted to the ER marks differentiating sieve elements in Arabidopsis, with esculin entering from mature sieve elements. (B) Electron micrograph showing mature and differentiating protophloem sieve elements embedded in dense stele tissue. (C,D) Symplasmic unloading demonstrates that small molecules like esculin spread to neighboring cells, while large proteins remain confined to the sieve tube system, showing size selectivity of unloading.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.21": (
    caption: [The unloading pathway can switch from an apoplastic to a symplasmic pathway. GFP fluorescence (green) and chlorophyll autofluorescence (red) show the developmental transition in unloading mechanism. (A) In a developing ovule of a closed flower, GFP is confined to the phloem due to absence of functional plasmodesmata. The switch to symplasmic unloading occurs as plasmodesmata develop, allowing direct cell-to-cell transport.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.22": (
    caption: [Autoradiographs of a summer squash leaf showing the transition from sink to source status. The leaf imported radioactive carbon from a source leaf for 2 hours, with label visible as black accumulations. (A) The entire leaf acts as a sink, importing sugar. (B-D) The base remains a sink while the tip transitions to source status, losing the ability to unload and gaining the ability to load and export sugar.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.23": (
    caption: [Division of labor in the veins of a tobacco leaf. (A) In an immature sink leaf, photosynthate is imported from mature leaves and distributed throughout the blade via major veins (numbered, with midrib as first-order vein). Imported photosynthate unloads from major veins into mesophyll. Minor veins are immature and nonfunctional. (B) In a mature source leaf, import ceases and export begins. Photosynthate loads into minor veins, while larger veins serve only in export and can no longer unload.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.24": (
    caption: [Export from source tissue depends on the placement and activity of active sucrose transporters. (A) Arabidopsis rosette with reporter gene under AtSUC2 promoter control showing blue staining (GUS activity) only in vascular tissue of source leaves and tips of transitioning leaves. SUC2 is a sucrose-H+ symporter functioning in phloem loading. (B,C) GFP fluorescence under SUC2 promoter control shows expression patterns correlating with source activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.25": (
    caption: [Allocation and partitioning determine the distribution of photosynthate within a plant. The diagram illustrates how fixed carbon from photosynthesis is allocated among different plant organs and partitioned between different metabolic processes. Allocation refers to the distribution among organs (roots, shoots, reproductive structures), while partitioning refers to the use within organs (growth, storage, respiration, reproduction).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12.26": (
    caption: [Glutamate released from damaged tissue triggers long-distance calcium-based defense signaling in the phloem. (A) Application of 100 mM glutamate to a wild-type Arabidopsis plant triggers propagation of a calcium wave, visible as increased calcium sensor fluorescence in almost all leaves. (B) In a mutant lacking vascular glutamate receptors, the same glutamate treatment does not produce long-distance signal propagation, demonstrating that glutamate mimics wounding responses through vascular receptor-mediated signaling.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
)
